          "body": "Verse 8 is the psalm's most surprising moment. Without any reported external change — no rescue narrated, no enemy defeated, no sickness lifted — David turns and commands: 'Depart from me, all you who do iniquity, for the LORD has heard the voice of my weeping.' The confidence is total and its basis is stated: YHWH has heard. The perfect tense in Hebrew ('has heard,' 'receives') does not describe a hoped-for future but a settled past fact. Something has shifted in David's interior. This is the grammar of faith: declaring the answer before its arrival as evidence that the prayer has been received. The same move appears in Jesus's prayer at Lazarus's tomb: 'Father, I thank You that You have heard Me' — before the stone was rolled away (John 11:41-42). The pivot of Psalm 6 is not psychological recovery; it is theological reorientation — David's eyes have moved from his tears to his God."
