        "excerpt": "I am weary with my sighing; every night I make my bed swim, I dissolve my couch with my tears.",
        "body": "Verses 6-7 are the psalm's most physiologically intense passage and its most important pastoral concession: the body is a legitimate witness to the soul's condition. David is weary (*yaga'*) with groaning (*anachah*, sighing, groaning). The groaning is not occasional — it has exhausted him. Then the image that makes verse 6 unforgettable: 'Every night I make my bed swim, I dissolve my couch with my tears.' The bed — the one place of rest in the ancient world — has become saturated with the evidence of grief. The tears are not metaphorical. The hyperbole of 'flooding the bed' is the ancient Near Eastern poet's way of saying: this grief is liquid and overwhelming.\n\nVerse 7 narrows from the night-scene to the organ of perception. 'My eye has wasted away (*ashesh*, consumed, worn out) with grief; it has grown old (*ataq*, become ancient, moved on) because of all my adversaries.' The eye that should be clear and seeing has been dimmed by sustained sorrow. The cause is named: 'all my adversaries.' David's physical deterioration is not only from inner grief but from the sustained pressure of hostile opposition. The enemies appear here for the first time as contributing agents of his affliction.\n\nThe pastoral significance of verses 6-7 is enormous. The psalm does not rebuke David for weeping. It does not correct his grief with a reminder of God's promises. It records the weeping as the content of prayer — indeed, verse 8 will declare that YHWH heard 'the voice of my weeping' (*qol bekhi*). Tears are audible to God. Grief that cannot be articulated in words reaches God as sound. This is the Bible's deepest concession to human suffering: the body's tears are a form of speech before God. Jonathan Edwards, in 'Religious Affections,' argued that genuine piety is marked not by the absence of grief but by grief directed toward God — and Psalm 6 is his exhibit.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Anachah* (groaning, sighing) is the same word used for Israel's enslaved groaning in Egypt (Exod 2:24) — a groan that God heard and responded to. *Dimah* (tear, teardrop) is the physiological specific — not weeping in general but the liquid itself. The image of flooding the couch (*mittah*) is hyperbole, but hyperbole in service of honest testimony."
